# Planning your Koverse Solution

This section talks you through the five key sequential steps in your solution planning:

1. Identifying your unique business challenges. Before committing to a particular design direction, brainstorm the different ways a Koverse solution can address your specific needs.
2. Identifying data requirements. Assess the data stores you can make available to your solution, including the ones that might have special data sensitivities.
3. Designing a workstream. Map out how you want the data to flow through your solution, including any analytics transforms you will apply to precompute data algorithms.
4. Reviewing the Koverse APIs. Look over the list and categories of APIs available for building your solution, and learn what each one can do.
5. Sizing and scaling the solution architecture. Figure out how much disk space you&#39;ll need in the Apache Hadoop cluster that houses your solution.

## 1. Identifying your unique business challenges

How you use Koverse depends in part on the unique characteristics and requirements of your business. As you transform your business by digitizing existing processes and innovating new solutions, Koverse can help—as long as you maintain a clear sense of the priorities and expected outcomes that will serve your business needs.

As a first step in planning a Koverse solution, take time to consider all of the opportunities for business improvement that a new digital platform might provide. Ask:

- **Where are the current EFFICIENCY GAPS in your business operations?** Take a close look at your day-to-day operations, from marketing and sales to fulfillment and customer service. Examine each step along the way, and look for areas for improvement—for example, where one process is idle because it&#39;s waiting for the output or resolution of another.
- **What manual processes can you AUTOMATE?** As you review your operations, identify opportunities to replace manual processes with tasks that can be digitized and automated using your available data.
- **How do you take your current business to the NEXT LEVEL?** How can your business become better? What services have you identified a market for, but never implemented? What changes to your current offerings will give you a competitive edge?
- **What IT projects have you PUT OFF in the past?** You&#39;ve probably had ideas for fixing inefficiencies or growing your business in the past, but have felt held back by the technology investment required to build solutions. Bring back those ideas and see if they can be developed using a Koverse workstream.
- **What DATA are you collecting that is going unused?** Keep in mind that the key strength of Koverse is its ability to help you manipulate data at scale without the need for expensive DBMS operations. Try reverse-engineering your business requirements by examining your existing data stores and asking in what ways the data can be put to better use.
- **What value can you add to your CUSTOMER experience?** The easier and more compelling it is for your customers and business partners to use your solution, the better engagement and interaction you can expect. Talk to your customers and find out what kinds of service changes or improvements will help you better meet their expectations.
- **What value can you add to your EMPLOYEE experience?** Empowered workers are not only more productive, but like customers and partners, they will serve your business best when they are engaged and can do more for themselves. Find ways to achieve this engagement by zeroing in on gaps where employees currently feel restricted in the ways they do their jobs.

Remember—this is an opportunity to brainstorm. As you complete this step, don&#39;t feel compelled to ideate new solutions quite yet. It&#39;s more about gathering requirements at this point, including the easy ones and the ones that might feel way out of reach.

## 2. Identifying data requirements

Once you have a sense of the business challenges you want to address, start making a list of the data sets that will need to be part of the Koverse solution. Again, don&#39;t try to design the actual solution just yet—simply account for the data that will be needed. You&#39;ll have a chance to link the data together in the next step.

One helpful way to approach this step might be to think about the final UI for the app you&#39;ll ultimately build using Koverse. What operations will take place in that UI? For each operation, work backwards to determine the data sets that will be required. Make notes as you go about the purpose of each data set within the overall solution, and what types of manipulations (sorting, cleanup, abstractions, computations, etc.) might be required to make the data useful for your purposes.

Some data sets will be obvious, but push yourself to identify additional data sets that you might have overlooked and that might also add value to your solution. Keep in mind that Koverse, by design, &quot;flattens out&quot; your data stores and allows you to get to the data without a DBMS, so the limitations of a traditional database application don&#39;t necessarily apply. Don&#39;t let what was previously unfeasible hold you back.

### Addressing data sensitivities

As part of this step, also make careful notes about the sensitivities related to each data set you specify. Koverse is a secure platform that integrates data access permissions into all of the operations you design your solution to perform. As such, key to planning your end-to-end solution will be accounting for these sensitivities so you can include them as you build each data set into your workstream.

## 3. Designing a workstream

Now, start connecting your data operations together to build the workstream for your solution. As with the previous step, try starting with the end in mind—how do you want the final UI to present your business information? Then, work backward to each data set and determine the flow of data through your solution, including the ways you want the data to be queried, manipulated, and acted upon at each step along the way.

### Applying transforms

As you build out your workstream, you&#39;ll need to make decisions about the analytics you want to perform in order to achieve your desired results.

Koverse uses _transforms_ to achieve distributed data processing—that is, to access one set of data and perform analytics to produce a new set of output. Transforms are the key to getting the most value out of your Koverse solution, because they enable you to access data right where you&#39;ve loaded it onto disk, and store the results on disk as well, where the new data sets become searchable and available to other solution elements.

The UI of the application you build as part of your solution will include the transforms you need to abstract data entities, detect anomalies, clean up data, or perform whatever other functions on your data are needed for producing the output that solves your business problem and delivers the value your solution provides. As long as the transform contains a reference to the raw data you loaded, your application UI can perform the transform algorithms and other operations on your data.

### Transforms vs. query-time analytics

Transforms are a powerful way to achieve data analytics without the need for a DBMS. However, not all data operations in your solution will benefit from transforms. In some cases, traditional SQL queries are preferable, depending on what you&#39;re trying to do. Koverse can include both UI-based precomputations (transforms) of your data and database queries (SQL queries) to deliver output.

As you plan your solution, figure out which method to use for each of your data operations, so that the solution you develop performs optimally. The following table includes our recommendations for SQL queries to use and which ones to avoid.

| **Data operations** | **Recommendations** |
| --- | --- |
| **Query with your application UI** | **Precompute using transforms** |

## 4. Reviewing the Koverse APIs

Koverse includes a set of APIs developers can access to build your customized solution. The APIs fall into four main categories:

- **Integration.** Use these APIs to ingest, export, and authenticate your data sets.
- **Analytics.** Use these APIs to apply Koverse transforms on your data sets.
- **Web development.** Use these APIs to build the UI for your solution.
- **Automation.** Use these APIs to selectively automate parts of your solution.

Detailed documentation of these APIs is included in the _Koverse API Reference_, including descriptions of all methods and parameters, and code examples to help with implementation. For now, you can review the APIs while looking at the workstream you&#39;ve created to determine the development efforts required to build your solution.

**Important:** As you&#39;ll see in the next step, the Koverse architecture isn&#39;t designed for live scaling, but rather for scaling in disk capacity to meet your solution&#39;s demands. So, although Koverse includes APIs for automation, these APIs are intended to automate parts of your solution selectively, not necessarily your entire solution as a whole. If your solution ideas include large-scale automation, work with our technical personnel to determine the best strategy for supporting your automation needs using the platform.

## 5. Sizing and scaling the solution architecture

Koverse installations are configured as Apache Hadoop clusters. The _Koverse System Administrator and Permissions Guide_ provides detailed infrastructure specifications and installation guidance, but for now, just know that in order to run Koverse, you&#39;ll be building out a Hadoop cluster—generally in the same way you&#39;d build one out for any other purpose.

That said, the final step in planning your solution is to get a rough idea of how much disk space your Hadoop cluster should include. As you determine this, keep a few important things in mind:

- Koverse works on the principal of &quot;flat&quot; storage of your data in disk-based data stores. Because of the relative affordability of disk space, plan your solution to comfortably accommodate the data stores you&#39;ll be using.
- For best results, maintain your Koverse solution on a dedicated Hadoop architecture, not a cluster that is shared with other applications.
- We don&#39;t recommend using VMware or other virtualized technologies as part of your Koverse solution.

So, how much disk space is enough? The answer depends mostly on three variables: how much data you&#39;ll need to load, how many jobs you want to run concurrently, and the complexity of the analytics (transforms) your solution will perform.

As the following drawing shows, you can start your solution small as long as your total disk capacity accommodates your data needs and you&#39;ll mostly be running a low volume of search queries against the data. For larger data sizes and/or complex data analytics, you&#39;ll want to size the solution larger so you can optimize its performance.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

DRAFT: Fig. x. Trade-offs to consider when sizing a Koverse solution.

Because Koverse uses disk space to store raw data, your solution can scale up easily by simply adding more disk space when you need it. With this in mind, we recommend assessing the total disk space your raw data will require, and then starting with 1.5 times that amount for your cluster. You can then add disk capacity as needed over time.
